<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-03-11T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-03-11T22:00:00-05:00" n="615" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d615">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01 Manchuria/33: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="#p_JNT1" type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-03-12T11:00:00+08:00">March 12, 1932—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 12—5:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>329. Following from the American Consul General, Mukden: <list>
                                <label>1.</label>
                                <item><quote rend="blockquote">“March 11, noon. The principal
                                        officials of the new government, appointed by the Regent on
                                        March 10th, are as reported in my despatch of March 7th
                                        except <persName corresp="#p_CC4">Chang Ching-hui</persName>
                                        who is head of the councilors <persName corresp="#p_YC3">Yuan</persName> or Privy Council. Other members of the
                                        Privy Council are <persName corresp="#p_TY1">Tang
                                            Yu-lin</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_YC3">Yuan
                                            Chin-kai</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_CH1">Chang
                                            Hai-peng</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_LC4">Lo
                                            Cheng-yu</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_KP1">Kuei
                                            Fu</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_CH3">Chao
                                            Hsin-po</persName> was appointed Chief of the
                                        Legislative <persName corresp="#p_YC3">Yuan</persName>.”</quote></item>
                                <label>2.</label>
                                <item>Other important officials mentioned in despatch of March 7th,
                                    referred to above, are: <persName corresp="#p_CH4">Cheng
                                        Hsiao-hsu</persName>, Premier; <persName corresp="#p_HC3">Hsi Hsia</persName>, Minister of Finance and Governor of
                                    Kirin; <persName corresp="#p_MC1">Ma Chan-shan</persName>,
                                    Minister of War and Governor of Heilungkiang; <persName corresp="#p_TS1">Tsang Shih-yi</persName>, Minister of Civil
                                    Administration and Governor of Fengtien; <persName corresp="#p_HC4">Hsieh Chieh-shih</persName>, Minister for
                                    Foreign Affairs.</item>
                            </list></p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>